featured_question.question: History of Konark temple
featured_question.answer:
(Translated by Google) The Sun Temple of Konark is amazing, unimaginable and fascinating. Our rich past can be seen here peeping through the broken rocks.
The sculptures of Belbute, various animals, gods, snakes and men and women are carved in stone with such beauty that it cannot be believed that these are man-made.
The vastness of the temple and the vast size of the area forces one to think about how it might have been constructed 800 years ago. How the huge stones might have been raised to the height.
No matter how much you imagine or whatever I write, it will be less for this temple.
This temple dedicated to the Sun God was built in the shape of a chariot with seven horses symbolizing the seven colors of sunlight, which is now in a ruined state.
This chariot-shaped temple has 24 wheels which symbolize 24 dynamic hours (night and day = 24 hours).
There are 8 sections attached to each wheel of the chariot, which are symbols of the 8 hours. There are different crafts inscribed on each wheel, which are related to social life, society, family, devotion, governance, penance, war, etc. Each wheel is depicted differently from the other. Are.

featured_reviews.review_id:
A majestic monument... It was amazing to visit and know more about this place. Our Indian heritage is so rich and scientifically amusing, which I only got to know after knowing about the temple. A very ambitious place. You can enjoy the beauty of stone arts and attractive green nature around it. In the evening you can enjoy the light and sound show...
Do not forget to take a guide along if you are visiting the temple. Easy access to Wheelchair at entry, for the aged visitos
Best time is between mid-November to mid-January

What amazing architecture and craftsmanship.

This place will mesmerize you and will leave you  wondering how skillful and knowledge our ancestors were.

There is ample of parking available inside which is chargeable and from there you have to walk towards temple.

On the way there would be museum also.

Ticket can be bought offline standing in queue and also online which is 5 rps cheaper.

While going out there is also a large flee market where you can buy many handicraft things...

featured_reviews.review_id: The sun temple, the greatest art of Odisha. The temple is full of architecture and beautiful stone arts. You can enjoy the beauty of stone arts and attractive green nature around it. Like the other temples of Odisha this temple also has story. The architecture of this temple is very detailed. The iron pillar, the wheels and the whole structure of this temple is so mesmerizing. But many of them are broken. In the evening you can enjoy the light and sound show. Do not forget to take a guide along if you are visiting the temple. Best time is between mid-November to mid-January.

featured_reviews.review_id:
The Konark Sun Temple is very beautiful and a must visit place. It shows the intelligence of the ancient Indian architectures.
There is are sun dial also which shows the real time according to the shadow which is amazing and the most important part of the temple.
The history behind this structure will definitely surprise you.
But the sun shines very bright there, so keep your sunglasses with you and also do not forget your hat or cap whatever you want to carry.
In short, I would like to say that it is a very beautiful historical architectural structure where you can and you should visit with your family and friends.
This place is wheelchair accessible also.

featured_reviews.review_id:
India has been a great country in any century in the past; Konark Sun Temple is a living example of that. The beauty of the carved stones is so great, especially on the wheels, that it makes you wonder how it was built without any modern-day machines.
If possible, take a guide along or read beforehand about the temple and the meaning of the design of the wheels. This way, you'll enjoy your visit more as it will make more sense when you look at the architecture and carvings.
Since we get to see the temple from outside only, it takes about one hour to see it completely. The entry ticket is priced at INR 40 for Indians and INR 600 for foreigners.
